We next developed a solvent exchange method to prepare CMC CDs@Cellulose with room-temperature long afterglow (Fig. 2 a). Microcrystalline cellulose was first dissolved in a solution of NaOH and urea, and then an aqueous solution of CMC CDs was added dropwise into the cellulose solution. Then, the as-obtained CMC CDs@Cellulose underwent a substantial purification by centrifugation, washing, and freeze-drying. The formation of CDs@Cellulose involves a number of distinct changes in the cellulose. Firstly, the glucopyranose rings of the cellulose molecules stack together through hydrophobic van der Waals interactions to form molecular sheets; secondly, these sheets produce thin planar crystals, which incorporate amorphous chains through hydrogen bonds; and finally, these structures make contact and link together to form fibrils in the solution [62]. During these transformations, the CMC CDs were successfully embedded in the cellulose matrix, as shown in Fig. 2b. The X-ray diffraction (XRD) pattern of the microcrystalline cellulose (Fig. 2c) showed signals at 14.6°, 16.6° and 22.98°, which were attributed to the (101), (10
1 ¯
) and (002) planes of cellulose I. In contrast, in the XRD pattern of CMC CDs@Cellulose, all the peaks of cellulose I disappeared and new diffraction peaks at 10.16°and 20.01°emerged, showing that a crystal transformation occurred with the formation of cellulose II. The strong peak at 22.17°was assigned to the (110) plane of urea, which was adsorbed onto the surface of the cellulose II. The XPS survey spectrum showed that the CMC CDs@Cellulose contained the elements C, N, O and Na, providing further evidence that the CMC CDs were really embedded in the cellulose matrix (Fig. 2d). Thermal stability of the CMC CDs@Cellulose was also studied (Supplementary Fig. S5). The weight loss was ∼7% nearby 100 °C, attributed to the evaporation of adsorbed water or humidity in cellulose. Further heating triggered the continuous decomposition of cellulose [63]. This result suggested that CDs@Cellulose was stable in ambient environment.
